  "prompt": "What are semaphores?",
  "response": "Semaphores are a synchronization mechanism used in concurrent programming to control access to shared resources and manage synchronization between multiple threads or processes. Here's a comprehensive overview:\n\n1. Basic Concept:\n- A semaphore is an integer variable used for signaling between threads\n- It maintains a count representing available resources or permits\n- Provides atomic operations to increment and decrement the count\n\n2. Types of Semaphores:\na) Binary Semaphore:\n- Has only two possible values (0 or 1)\n- Similar to a mutex lock\n- Used for simple mutual exclusion\n\nb) Counting Semaphore:\n- Can have multiple values\n- Tracks available resources\n- Allows multiple threads to access resources simultaneously\n\n3. Key Operations:\na) wait() / P() / acquire():\n- Decrements semaphore count\n- Blocks thread if count is zero\n- Prevents resource access when unavailable\n\nb) signal() / V() / release():\n- Increments semaphore count\n- Wakes up waiting threads\n- Indicates resource is now available\n\n4. Common Use Cases:\n- Resource management\n- Thread synchronization\n- Producer-consumer problems\n- Preventing race conditions\n\n5. Example Scenarios:\n- Controlling database connections\n- Limiting concurrent file access\n- Managing thread pool resources\n\n6. Implementation Characteristics:\n- Atomic operations\n- Thread-safe\n- Can prevent deadlocks when used correctly",
